Business Overview

Understanding the core business provides context for the following analysis. Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company Limited, together with its subsidiaries, manufactures, packages, tests, and sells integrated circuits and other semiconductor devices in Taiwan, China, Europe, the Middle East, Africa, Japan, the United States, and internationally. It provides various wafer fabrication processes, such as processes to manufacture complementary metal- oxide-semiconductor (CMOS) logic, mixed-signal, radio frequency, embedded memory, bipolar CMOS mixed-signal, and others.

The company also involved in providing customer and engineering support services; manufacturing of masks; investment in technology start-up companies; research, designing, developing, manufacturing, packaging, testing, and sale of color filters;

and investment activities. Its products are used in high performance computing, smartphones, Internet of things, automotive, and digital consumer electronics. The company was incorporated in 1987 and is headquartered in Hsinchu City, Taiwan.

Share Statistics

Nearly all of the company's 5 B shares are publicly available as float, so no major amount is locked up. However, investors should be aware that the company could issue more shares, potentially diluting the value of existing stock. Executives and major shareholders own very little of the company (0.04%), meaning they may not have substantial 'skin in the game' if the company struggles. The level of ownership by institutions is also small, coming in at 16.28%. This is much less than the averages found in widely held stocks. If big-money investors are avoiding the stock, it could be due to concerns about performance or simply a lack of focus on the company.

We will now look into the impact of short interest on the market. When we look at all of these factors, we can see that while the stock is liquid and easy to trade, its price may not see sustained growth unless it gains stronger support from large institutional traders or company insiders.

Profitability and Growth

An analysis of the key metrics in TSM's margin performance shows the company has solid control over its costs and prices. The company is successful in controlling its production costs, as shown by the gross margin of 58.98%, and it also profits well from its core operations, reflected in the 50.58% operating margin. A 68.42% EBITDA margin indicates TSM is capable of generating strong cash flow from its operations before accounting for financing and tax strategies. All things considered, TSM can hold onto around $43.290 in net profit for every $1 of its revenue over the last twelve months. While the business's revenue is increasing at an aggressive rate (30.30%), investors should monitor if this pace can be sustained without eroding profit margins.

TSM's 2.48 T in EBITDA and 2.14 T in gross profit indicate its raw earning power, while the 1.57 T in net income reveals how effectively it converts that power into bottom-line results. The company appears to be balancing its pursuit of growth with the need to maintain profitability. Despite healthy gross margins, there is a significant difference between the company's gross and net margins (58.98% vs. 43.29%). This is likely due to high operating expenses, interest costs, or taxes, which are key areas for investors to watch. In the future, maintaining steady or improving margins will be critical. TSM needs to defend its pricing power and control operating costs, as this will help sustain profitability, especially if revenue growth moderates.

Dividends and Shareholder Returns

Dividend Summary & Investor Implications

The company currently offers a $3.37 annual dividend per share, translating to a dividend yield of 1.16%‚Äîmeaning for every $100 invested, shareholders receive $3.37 in dividends annually. This yield is below the 5-year average of 1.64%, suggesting that either the stock price has risen (reducing the yield) or dividend growth hasn't kept pace with historical trends.

Key Observations & Analysis:

  • The payout ratio of 29.79% is low and conservative, indicating the company uses only ~30% of its earnings to fund dividends. This leaves ample room for future increases or reinvestment in growth.
  • The very low trailing yield of 7.00% hints at a recent dividend initiation or a special, non-recurring payout, warranting further checks for consistency.
  • Investors must own the stock before the upcoming ex-dividend date of 2025-12-11 to receive the next dividend.
  • The last stock split (1005:1000 in 2009) is outdated and likely irrelevant to the current valuation.

Investor Takeaway:

  • Income Investors: The modest yield and low payout ratio suggest dividends are safe but not a primary reason to invest. The focus may be on future dividend growth.
  • Growth Investors: The low payout ratio is a strong signal that a majority of earnings are being reinvested, which could drive future price appreciation.
  • Watch For: Announcements of dividend hikes (which could bring the yield closer to its historical average) or significant stock price changes that would alter the yield.
